00:13:55.180 --> 00:13:57.590
- This view I had that
they were flat lining

00:13:57.590 --> 00:13:59.470
turned out to be quite false.

00:13:59.470 --> 00:14:03.090
I had sort of imagined a very
simple mathematical model.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:06.020
You can create something
called a rectangular hyperbola,

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:08.760
I guess, which has an initial high slope

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:10.950
and then reaches an asymptote,

00:14:10.950 --> 00:14:13.410
but they're equally simple models.

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:15.460
There's a model that also
has just two parameters

00:14:15.460 --> 00:14:19.220
called a power law model
that says things slow down,

00:14:19.220 --> 00:14:20.690
but it doesn't have an upper bound.

00:14:20.690 --> 00:14:23.210
It says, just keep going
for time immemorial,

00:14:23.210 --> 00:14:25.330
and things will just keep going faster,

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:28.700
but at a slower and slower
rate of further improvement.

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:32.110
And it turned out that
model actually fits our data

00:14:32.110 --> 00:14:35.290
better than that original
model I had imagined.

00:14:35.290 --> 00:14:37.670
And not only does it fit it better,

00:14:37.670 --> 00:14:40.460
okay, you say statistics,
science, fitting curves,

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:41.960
it actually predicts the future.

00:14:41.960 --> 00:14:45.410
And that's what's really cool
because the original model,

00:14:45.410 --> 00:14:47.910
if you give it say just 5,000 generations

00:14:47.910 --> 00:14:49.370
worth of our fitness data

00:14:49.370 --> 00:14:51.650
